ion in the United States. This book argues that lessons for addressing these national challenges are emerging from a new set of realities in America's metropolitan regions: first, that inequity is, in fact, bad for economic growth; second, that bringing together the concerns of equity and growth requires concerted local action; and, third, that the fundamental building block for doing this is the creation of diverse and dynamic epistemic (or knowledge) communities, which help to overcome political polarization and help regions address the challenges of economic restructuring and social divides.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCities and townszUnited StatesxEconomic policy. 0aEconomic development projectszUnited StatesxCase studies. 0aEconomic developmentxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aIncome distributionzUnited States. 0aRegional planningzUnited StatesxCase studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Urban.2bisacsh1 aPastor, Manuel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z978311062111240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780520960046?locatt=mode:legacyzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520960046zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520960046/original  a978-3-11-062111-2 University of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA